'''Uge Shrine''' (うげじんじゃ; {{ill|lt=kyūjitai|Q1147857|WD=Q1147857|1=Kyūjitai}}: 宇藝神社) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kannari, {{ill|lt=Tomioka|Q873835|WD=Q873835|1=Tomioka, Gunma}}, {{ill|lt=Gunma Prefecture|Q129499|WD=Q129499|1=Gunma Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}{{Sfn|Honda|1928|pp=817-819}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|lt=Kura-inetama-no-Kami|1=Ukanomitama}} (うかのみたまのかみ){{Sfn|Honda|1928|pp=817-819}}<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|和書 |title=History of Tomioka City |date=1984-10-1 |year=1984 |publisher=Tomioka City |page=421 |doi=10.11501/9643274 |editor=Tomioka City History Editorial Committee |volume=Folklore volume}}{{要登録}}</ref>

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was founded in the Hakuhō era (late {{ill|lt=7th century|Q8089|WD=Q8089|1=7th century}}), in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenmu|Q335181|WD=Q335181|1=Emperor Tenmu}}{{Sfn|Honda|1928|pp=817-819}}. The present shrine site was originally where Akagi Shrine stood, and Uge Shrine was originally on the west side near Yoshida Pond{{Sfn|Honda|1928|pp=817-819}}<ref name=":0" />.

In the {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it is listed as "Uge Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Kanra District|Q1076986|WD=Q1076986|1=Kanra District, Gunma}}, {{ill|lt=Kōzuke Province|Q1054838|WD=Q1054838|1=Kōzuke Province}}, and is ranked as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}{{Sfn|Ozaki|1974|pp=40}}.

In the ''Kōzuke no Kuni Jinmyōchō'', both the {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya Nukisaki Shrine|Q10863796|WD=Q10863796|lt=Ichinomiya|1=Nukisaki Shrine}} manuscript and the {{ill|lt=Gunsho Ruijū|Q1554852|WD=Q1554852|1=Gunsho Ruijū}} manuscript include "Junior First Rank, Ugi Daimyōjin" among the 12 guardian shrines of Kōzuke, and this is identified with this shrine<ref name=":0" />. On the other hand, the {{ill|lt=Sōja Shrine (Maebashi)|Q17220813|WD=Q17220813|lt=Sōja|1=Sōja Shrine (Maebashi)}} manuscript does not include it among the 10 guardian shrines. In the Kanra District section, the Ichinomiya manuscript has "Junior First Rank, Ugi Daimyōjin," while the Gunsho Ruijū and Sōja manuscripts have "Junior First Rank, Sōgi Myōjin." {{ill|lt=Ozaki Kisao|Q21698487|WD=Q21698487|1=Kisao Ozaki}} regarded the guardian-shrine entry and district entry as different shrines, assigning the latter to Soki Shrine (Soki, Tomioka){{Sfn|Ozaki|1974|pp=46,192-196}}.

It was destroyed by fire during the {{ill|lt=Tenmei|Q1194121|WD=Q1194121|1=Tenmei}} era ({{ill|lt=1781|Q7719|WD=Q7719|1=1781}}-{{ill|lt=1789|Q7772|WD=Q7772|1=1789}}), and the current shrine buildings are said to have been rebuilt in April of {{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1716|Q6892|WD=Q6892|1=1716}})<ref>{{ill|lt=Kyōwa|Q960763|WD=Q960763|1=Kyōwa}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1801|Q6877|WD=Q6877|1=1801}})?</ref>{{Sfn|Honda|1928|pp=817-819}}.

The festival date was November 3, but is now April 3 and October 15<ref name=":0" />.

=== Precincts ===
* Honden - one-bay {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}}.
* Haiden
* Mukuroji tree - 14 m tall, about 300 years old. Designated natural monument of Tomioka City.
* Precinct shrines<ref name=":0" />
** Akagi Shrine
** Takaokami Shrine
** Santai Shrine
** Shinmeigū
** Mishima Shrine
** Fuji Shrine
** Kotohira-gū
** Hokuto Shrine
** Ōikazuchi Shrine
